    "John Trapp": "Then Joshua. ] After the spies were returned. { #Jos 2:23 }\nVer.\n10. Then Joshua `[object_Joshua_Jos_2]`.] After the spies were returned. {#Jos 2:23}\nVer.\n10. And they slew Sheshai, &amp;c. ] Those huge giants were slain by such as seemed but grasshoppers unto them. See #Jos 11:21,22 .\n10. And they slew Sheshai `[char_Sheshai_Num_13]`, &c.] Those huge giants were slain [v_Jos_11_21] by such as seemed but grasshoppers unto them. See #Jos 11:21,22. [v_Jos_15_15]\n10. Surely we will return with thee. ] So they both said, and said as they thought: but Orpah, upon second thoughts, did otherwise. Saul in a passion promised fair, { #1Sa 24:16,17 26:21 } but David `[char_David_Rut_4]` knew there was no trusting to either his tears or his talk.\nVer.\n10. Surely we will return with thee.] So they both said, and said as they thought: but Orpah, upon second thoughts, did otherwise. Saul in a passion promised fair, {#1Sa 24:16,17 26:21} but David `[char_David_Rut_4]` knew there was no trusting to either his tears or his talk.\nVer.\n10. And she was in bitterness of soul, and prayed. ] Herein she took a right course to get comfort. So did David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, { #Ps 109:4 } and Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`, { #1Co 4:13 } \"being defamed we pray.\" If she should have rendered to Peninnah railing for railing, there would have been somewhat to do. Prayer and patience are the best antidotes against contempt and contumelies; the one hot, the other cold; the one quickening, the other quenching. And wept sore. ] Prayers and tears are the saints\u2019 best weapons; Bombardae et instrumenta bellica Christianorum, saith Luther, their great guns, and their scaling ladders.\nVer.\n10. And she was in bitterness of soul, and prayed.] Herein [v_Psa_109_4] she took a right course to get comfort. So did David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, {#Ps 109:4} and Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`, {#1Co 4:13} \"being defamed we pray.\" If she should have rendered to Peninnah railing for railing, there would have been somewhat to do. Prayer and patience are the best antidotes against contempt and contumelies; the one hot, the other cold; the one quickening, the other quenching. And wept sore.] Prayers and tears are the saints\u2019 best weapons; Bombardae et instrumenta bellica Christianorum, saith Luther, their great guns, and their scaling ladders.\nVer.\n10. That great apostle was \"in death often\"; and those ancient confessors cry out, \"For thy [v_Rom_8_36] sake are we killed all the day long.\" {#Ro 8:36} The Hebrews say that Peninnah\u2019s children died all but two, and that those were saved alive by Hannah\u2019s prayer for them, at their mother\u2019s request.\nVer.\n10. The adversaries of the Lord shall be broken to pieces.] [v_Psa_2_9] \"As a potter\u2019s vessel.\" {#Ps 2:9} Turk and Pope, both those Antichrists, shall be served on this sort, saith Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` Martyr. Out of heaven shall he thunder upon them.] As he did soon after this prophecy upon the Philistines. {#1Sa 7:10} The mightiest men quake before God, and as the worms when it thundereth, wriggle into their holes. The Lord shall judge the ends of the earth.] The Lord Christ shall; who is here first of all in Scripture called Messiah, or the Anointed One, of whom David `[char_David_Rut_4]` and Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` were types; and in that sense may also be here understood.\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 50": "Maimon. Obede Cochabim, c. 5. sect. 3.\nft129 --  Maimon. Obede Cochabim, c. 4. sect. 3. 6.\nft130 --  Misn. Sanhedrin, c. 11. sect. 6.\nft131 --  lbid. Maimon. & Bartenora in ib.\nft132 --  Vid. Virgil. Aeneid. 12.\n10. Vid. Buxtorf. Synagog. Jud. c. 25. p.\n522, 523.\nft444 --  Hilchot Sanhedrin, c. 17. sect. 1.\nft445 --  Ibid. sect. 7, 8, 9.\nft446 --  Antiqu. l. 4. c. 8. sect. 21.\nft447 --  Hilchot Shecirut, c. 13. sect. 2, 3.\nft448 --  Hist. Animal. l. 4. c. 25.\nft449 --  Hilchot Yebum Vechalitzah, c, 1, sect, 7.\nft450 --  Misn. Yebamot, c. 4. sect. 5.\nft451 --  Yebamot, c. 4. sect. 5.\nft452 --  Ib. sect. 10.\nft453 --  Ut supra, sect. 3. (Leo Modena\u2019s History of Rites, etc. l. 1 sect."
